data.title: How Charles's cousin King Harald V of Norway, 86, survived WWII exile
data.meta_description: King Harald V of Norway is the closest European monarch to the British Royal family: he is a second cousin to the late Queen through Queen Victoria and Prince Albert's oldest son, Edward VII.
data.text:
King Harald V of Norway is a three-time Olympic sailor, but a simple balcony appearance for Norwegian National Day was something of an achievement.

For the 86-year-old is in fragile health and has only recently come out of hospital - for the second time in six months - after surviving an infection.

With his wife, Queen Sonja, by his side, King Harald waved to thousands of children marching in front of the Oslo's Royal Palace, many of them in National Costume.

It was a distinctively Norwegian occasion, yet Harald remains extremely close to our Royal Family - and in fact is 77th in line to the British throne.

He is a great-grandson of Edward VII and his godparents included Queen Mary and her son George VI (grandmother and father respectively of the late Queen Elizabeth).

Like his late second cousin the Queen, he has been an active monarch, although his 32-year reign does not match up to Her Majesty's 70 years on the throne.

And he has proven himself strong-willed too, having insisted on marrying his wife Queen Sonja, despite opposition to the union because she was a 'commoner'.

Born on February 21, 1937 at the Skaugum estate near Oslo, Harald is the son of the King Olav V and his wife Princess Martha of Sweden.

In April 1940, when Harald was just three, the security of a princely upbringing was shattered when Nazi Germany invaded Norway.

Harald and his two older sisters, Ragnhild and Astrid, were swept up by their mother and taken first to Sweden.

Whilst Harald's father and grandfather - the reigning King Haakon VII - held out in Norway as their heroic countrymen battled the German invasion, they too finally fled in June and headed to London with the Norwegian government-in-exile.

In August that year, Harald and his mother and sisters then went to the United States, where they spent the rest of the war, living in Washington.

Crown Prince Olav and King Haakon - whose wife Queen Maud (sister of George V) had died in 1938 - were initially guests at Buckingham Palace.

A young Princess Elizabeth at one point found them 'both snoring away' on the floor of the royal air raid shelter.

'Tho' we love having them,' she told her grandmother, Queen Mary, 'it is rather a bore never to be alone'.

But Haakon did make himself useful by persuading King George VI - his first cousin - to test out his royal protection arrangements after suffering a failed kidnap attempt back home.

George VI pressed the designated alarm button but there was no immediate response. Eventually a few bemused guardsmen appeared.

After that a Coldstream Guards officer Major TS 'Jimmy' Coats was put in charge of royal protection.

In June 1945, Prince Harald - now aged seven - returned with his family to Norway, after Nazi Germany's defeat in the war.

During five years of occupation, the royal palace had been turned into a prison, whilst ordinary Norwegians had been starved.

Arriving by boat, King Haakon was said to have been so deeply moved that he was unable to speak for several minutes.

The Daily Mail told how he 'stood, a tall, slim, immaculate figure, while thousands of his subjects, jammed in the narrow flag-smothered streets of Oslo, raised the mightiest welcome shout ever heard in Norway  a wild, prolonged yell that echoed for miles down the misty fjords.'

Prince Harald was coming back with his family at a time when there was still danger everywhere.

There were still hundreds of thousands of Germans on Norwegian soil, including soldiers billeted near the quay, waiting to be moved to prison camps.

But the King still insisted on riding in an open car, projecting an image of defiance to his newly liberated subjects.

The Daily Mail told how he was then treated to the 'greatest procession ever seen in Scandinavia', with 80,000 people from 'every phase of Norwegian life' filing past the King.

But there were signs of their poor treatment at the hands of their German occupiers, with every face in the procession bearing 'traces of the starvation Norway has undergone under the Nazi heel.'

In 1954, nine years after the family's return, they were hit by tragedy when Harald's mother died of cancer.

The Prince, then just 17, would go on to name his firstborn Mrtha in honour of her memory.

Three years later, King Haakon died at the age of 85, after nearly 52 years on the throne.

Harald, now the heir, went on to study at the University of Oslo and also enrolled in the Norwegian Military Academy, graduating in 1959.

It was at his graduation ball that he brought along the woman who would become his wife.

Harald had met Sonja Haraldsen, the daughter of an Oslo draper, earlier that year. It was her status as a commoner that ruffled royal feathers.

The pair initially kept their relationship a secret, but when it did become public knowledge, the Palace repeatedly insisted that the pair would not marry.

But when Harald threatened to remain a bachelor forever if he did not get his way, his father relented and let him wed the woman he loved.

Their 1968 wedding at Oslo Cathedral came after both had studied in England.

Whilst Sonja read English at Cambridge, Harald went to Oxford to study Politics, Philosophy and Economics at Balliol College.

The Anglophile became a keen rower, having been taught by renowned coach Nick Bevan, who was studying at the same college.

But sailing was his sport: he went on to represent Norway at the Olympics in Tokyo in 1964, Mexico City in 1968 and Munich in 1972.

His and Sonja's first child, Princess Mrtha Louise, was born in 1971, with her brother, Crown Prince Haakon, arriving the following year.

But Prince Haakon would have a long wait before he became first in line to the throne.

His father did not become king until January 1991, when he was 53.

Harald's closeness to King Charles was demonstrated five years later, when he went to Sandringham for a shooting weekend.

The monarch was also at Charles's 50th birthday party in 1998, when 250 guests descended on Highgrove.

In 2011, Harald was among the dozens of European royals who attended the wedding of the Prince and Princess of Wales and was a guest at the Queen's Diamond Jubilee Lunch the following year.

In another demonstration of the closeness between the Norwegian and English royal families, Her Late Majesty was the only head of to make three state visits to Norway, in 1955, 1981 and 2001.

In 1955, they arrived on the Royal Yacht Britannia, having sailed up the Oslo Fjord between what was described at the time as a 'lane of fire'.

'Every few miles along this island-dotted coastline, flames and sparks from midsummer bonfires shot skyward with red, white and blue rockets,' the Daily Mail reported.

Though not on a scale of the struggles of some of his British cousins, King Harald's family have had their own controversies.

King Harald's daughter, who was once a rumoured love interest of Prince Edward, has raised eyebrows over her choice of fiance: self-described shaman Durek Verrett.

He recently revealed he has discussed 'black culture and what I've been through' with the King and Queen - his would-be in-laws.

Verrett's celebrity followers include Gwyneth Paltrow, Nina Dobrev and James Van Der Beek.

Princess Martha, who is a self-proclaimed clairvoyant in her own right, claims that both she and her beau have 'spirital powers' which allowed her to foresee his plans to propose.

She was previously married to Norwegian author Ari Behn, but the pair divorced in 2017, two years before he took his own life at the age of just 47.

The couple had daughters Maud Angelica, Leah Isadora, and Emma Tallulah together.

In an echo of the move made by Prince Harry and his wife Meghan Markle, Princess Louise stepped down as a senior working royal last November so she could pursue commercial projects with her partner. But she still kept her royal title.

Harald will be hoping that his final years are free from any other difficulties.

In recent years, his health has taken a battering. He has used canes for several years and needed a leg operation last January.

He was then hospitalised at Christmas with an infection, four months after needing treatment for a fever.

However, he continues to be an active monarch. Just before his initial hospital visit last year, he even took part in the Sailing World Cup, where he finished in tenth.

If his health holds up, Harald is expected to travel to Britain for King Charles's Coronation in May, as he did for the Queen's funeral last September.
